deck_description: Ancient Gear GOAT
Sky Strikers

For a long time since the ban on Halquifibrax, Chaos ruler dragon and now recently spright elf, zombie combo has been very expensive, relying on playing bystials, branded, despia and turning the deck into a turbo doomking + mirrorjade. This evolution of the zombie deck as been just a worst branded deck, etc. 

I took sometime finally review the state of the deck and the cards to find out a way to re use all the new zombie support and play the deck as intended, ofcourse this will not win a tier 1 deck, its not meant to be anyways, but its fun enough to be consisten, put up interuptions and play the clasic zombie endboard of vampire + synchro 10 + eldlich with a facedown. This endboard is close enough to represent what zombie combo used to do, be able to synchro, link, fusion and even if you want you can change the extra to play xyz, o put in baldrake and try to make beatriz.

The reason its mixed with eldlich is because 1 eldlich on board can let u utilize black stone as a emergency teleport for the deck, this solves the issue with being negated on the normal, not being able to extend after etc. You can try to play more handtraps, or board breakers, but for this list i rather leave it as a clean and pure build and let others use this as a template for their own flavour, the objective of the deck is to combo, not control, eldlich is a neat engine that just helps the zombie build to be better.

If you are new to the deck, i will explain a bit the idea, (but in my opinion i think you should download the file and have fun experimenting to understand it before you read this)

Main combo line is usually any starter that goes uni-zombie/ send from deck to grave Changshi or hand, summon her/ extend by sending mad mauler (fun fact immortal dragon is generic), re-summon target the Changshi, summon immortal, send banshee, zombie world. At this point you did the basic part of the combo, the rest, you achieve it by extending, either a edlich setup to summon doomking with sanguine, while you have a red-eyes zombie dragon lord, that can revive de eldlich on draw phase, to use sanguine to bring doomking. Thats the basic part of the deck. Its a zombie tool-box deck inspired by the earth machine tool-box in a certain way.

Board breakers, Felgrand, Vampire Frauline, Shiranui solitaire to recylce the immortal dragon, vampire sucke to tribute summon using your opponents ZOMBIE monster, if you kill a dragoon, you can get it back with Frauline and laugh. One gripe with the extra is that i would maybe change 1 sucker for a superdreadnaught rail cannon gustav max for doing effect damage since having level 10 on field isnt that hard for the deck.

I guess you are wandering, why do you play the eldlich fusion spell? Well you see, if you draw a hand that doesnt have normal summons, or you have plenty of graveyard extenders, that spell lets you fusion ANYTHING, as long as you use zombies from your hand or field, its not a brick anymore, so with that fact, why not play garura? well as i said before this is a template, a idea that can get better or even lower the cost of the deck, i made this list for budget players and as a generic idea. The side deck is anything you want ignore whats on it.

What is it weak against? Heavy backrow decks tend to be tedious battles put being able to put large atackers tend to help the labrynth match up a bit, Kashtira because of the banish, bystial decks already have proven to kill anyother deck that plays light/dark and branded/despia/bystial kind of screws the deck over if its just despia branded, maybe you have a chance.

What our it strengths? Recursive graveyard, if you are not dead turn after turn 2, you pretty much already have plenty of interactions ready, its strong agains other rogue decks and can make up for a very fun duel thats back and forth winning depends onm the pilot 60% of the time so learn how this deck works, some lines look like bricks, but they are not, its consistent enough to always do something that you can use, jack-o-bolan is in the deck to also solve bricks or even use it as a tribute summon if you drew chengshi.

Gold Sarcophagus is the new foolish burial, any zombie in grave, + this cards is already a way to banish changshi and summon her, its just amazing.

Ready fusion: Gozuki + this card is also already full combo, i would dare to say i like this opening more.

Why 1 shiranui and 2 uni-zombie, drawing 2 uni zombie is a brick, its not a useful thing, uni zombie is a starter AND a brick, so playing 2 copies and 1 shiranui solved the problem for me.

deck_excerpt: New concepts for Megalith with new support for Ritual decks
deck_description:
About the new support for Ritual Summon decks: Link-2 Dyna Mondo

The first effect of the card is great because it basically replaces Knightmare Unicorn for Ritual decks without having to discard cards from your hand while recycling your Ritual monsters back to the deck.

For a deck like Megalith it has even more relevance because Megalith has difficulty putting many monsters on the table to make extra deck plays so it is the monster that interacts with the easiest access in the extra deck and becomes a crucial card during the games that go to the grind game.

The second effect is also very good in the Megalith deck because it has the versatility to replace the effect of the Megalith Portal to add a Ritual Monster from the GY to the hand or the Megalith Emergence to give Reborn.

That way post side deck you can choose to cut one of them for example and side deck cards in place.

 

Interesting points about the card:

He is an out via engine for Number 41: Bagooska. It has the down arrows which means you can make Knightmare Cerberus and Phoenix Co-Linked.

Now in Megalith in the weakest hands of the deck where usually you can only add the field spell Portal and the trap Emergence you still manage to turn your cards into one more interaction because you join any two monsters in I:P Masquerena and in the opponent's turn you manages to Reborn with Megalith Emergence of any Megalith other than Phul and make the Dyna Mondo from the deck and still use its second effect to bring Phul to the field and then Phul to bring Bethor.

In summary it basically becomes two interactions against the opponent being an essential card in Megalith.

 

//////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////

All the combos you can learn in this deck profile: https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/megalith-master-duel-apr22-format-264045

 

//////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////

One thing that I noticed and learned a lot when using Megalith is the fact that the deck uses 3 engines, the main one being Megalith, but without the other two engines of Impcantation and Fairy cards Manju and Benten, the deck makes a combo with few interactions and that has no good follow ups.

That's why it's always very important that you can access the other engines, both to be able to play second and to have more versatility and follow up, especially the Impcantation engine.

For that you can use Megalith Och and Cross-Sheep to draw new cards. No wonder I use Cross-Shrep because that way through the Megalith engine you can give 2 to 3 draws on the turn and improve your hand and even have more hand traps against the opponent.

Considering that this deck despite separating interactions does not do anything very impeding since via the engine you can only reach 3 interactions: Megalith Phul summons Megalith Bethor, Nibiru and a LINK-2 that interacts like Herald of Mirage Lights or I: P Masquerena so what you always want to do is survive the opponent's turn to take control of the game in the excellent grind game that the deck has.

That's why every decision is crucial to win using Megalith. You must know very well the right time to use your interactions. The deck has the main weaknesses related to having to first manage to rotate the main deck engine and only then use the extra deck, different from the best Ritual deck in the game, which is Drytron, which does not restrict you at all in the extra deck because you don't need it use the Impcantation engine.

So the main message I leave about Megalith is that it has very good consistency, it manages to interact in both turns and separate interactions, the engine is even able to play on negates and cards that destroy because it is easy to set up the field again because everything recycles, is capable of using a minimum of 11 tech cards in the main deck, and has an excellent grind game. What is missing for the deck is some improvement of the main deck that, for example, replaces Manju as a Normal Summon and also facilitates the Ritual summon without restricting access to the extra deck as Impcantation does, but otherwise this deck has a lot of potential in the hands of those who train quite.

deck_excerpt: Final version of the deck for the new format in the TCG, now it's just waiting for Transcendrake cards to improve the deck
deck_description:
Final version of the deck for the new format in the TCG

The Spright Elf card has huge synergy with the Dinosaur deck. The fact of not having access to it anymore makes the end board less solid against secondary blind cards and also with less follow ups. Some combos also get a lot worse like Scrap Raptor + Miscellaneousaurus.

Ultimately it can be replaced with other options like a LINK-2 Reprodocus, a LINK-2 Knightmare Cerberus or a LINK-2 Charmer or some XYZ RANK-4 option like Tornado Dragon. Of course I should use Math in the deck build to know what will be most effective.

 

////////////////////////////////////////////////// ////////////////////////////Combos and moves that complement the combos shown in the following decklist:

https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/dinosaur-scrap-ogdoadic-feb23-317551

 

////////////////////////////////////////////////// ////////////////////////////

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-46749390

COMBO 1: Diagram + Oviraptor/Babycerasaurus (use all 4 Babys)

 

You can take advantage of PSY-Framelord Omega in the deck with Ogdoadic cards. If you do it in the full combo which is when the opponent says he has no interactions:

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-46821212

COMBO 2: Oviraptor + Babycerasaurus + Nunu (FULL COMBO WITH THE BEST FOLLOW UPS POSSIBLE)

 

On the way back you already have half a RANK-8 to start breaking the field. That way it kind of plays the role of Chaos Ruler the next turn of the deck, of course Chaos Ruler is a much more powerful card but it has many qualities besides returning Miscellaneousaurus to the GY.

 

The engine of Ogodoadic Possible combos to force interactions:

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-46472210

Easy access to Exciton Knight, Dingirsu and AA-Zeus.

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-46745510

Snake Rain + 2 Discard = I:P Masquerena + Bagooska

 

////////////////////////////////////////////Card and gameplay comments:

Ogdoadic's engine is extremely horrible against Bystial cards. Any combination of 2 Bystial cards is enough to eliminate all Ogdoadic plays.

Even a single Bystial can ruin an Ogdoadic day and that's why I've decided that every game where I face Bystial I'm going to pull the entire 11 card engine from Ogdoadic because Bystial.

As Bystial are terrible against Dinosaur cards, I prefer to change the 11 Ogdoadic cards for new 11 Side Deck cards, because Omega can also return Miscellaneousaurus to the GY, which means that I will continue to have Follow Up.

 

This deck has a lot of brick so a Deck Build recommendation is to increase the number of cards above 40 because you reduce the chance of seeing your bricks which means continuing to have consistency. Jesse Kotton made a video talking about it on his channel called: The Heart Of The Cards is a Load of Rubbish! How to Improve at Yugioh #1

 

When using Pot of Prosperity you must make the right decision because this deck can very well activate Prosperity for 6 cards and you must ban cards that will not harm you according to Gamestate for example if you have not accessed the Ogdoadic engine you must keep the King of the Feral Imps.

- There is no clear card rule to banish going first but generally you can banish Linkuriboh, Omega, Phoenix, I:P Masquerena, Dweller (if you don't know you are facing Tearlaments), Bagooska and Cerberus.

- Field breaking cards like Exciton Knight, Dingirsu and AA-Zeus I always keep in the Extra Deck.

- As the engine of Ishizu Tearlaments mill your main deck cards for the GY it can happen that you mill the cards of Scrap Raptor so the Scrap Wyvern can also be a card to be banned with Prosperity but in general I keep it because it is a insane letter.

 

Finally, the most significant change made besides adding the Dragonic Diagram + True King Lithosagym engine was card Number 23: Lancelot, Dark Knight of the Underworld in place of Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy.

 

Advantages of Number 23:

- It is an omni negate every turn, that is, it plays the same role as Number 38 but also deals with traps like Evenly Matched. The opponent ends up also being taken by surprise when he sees that you accessed an omni negate with Ogdoadic's cards.

- It attacks the opponent directly making it easy for you to do AA-ZEUS in Main Phase 2 and clean the field by going over annoying cards like Avramax and Infinitrack Fortress Megaclops and any monsters with Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon protection like Borrelend Dragon to do AA-ZEUS.

- When he inflicts battle damage he destroys an opponent's monster so it's also a disruption in the battle phase.

Basically he's as good going first as Number 38: Harbinger and going second there's no comparison, it's much better.

- The only drawback I see on the card is the low ATK/DEF stat.

////////////////////////////////////////////////// ///////////

deck_excerpt: ygoprodeck.com, yugipedia.com, yugioh.fandom.com, yugiohtopdecks.com, ygorganization.com, rushcard.io, discordapp.com, imgur.com, youtube.co
deck_description: ygoprodeck.com, yugipedia.com, yugioh.fandom.com, yugiohtopdecks.com, ygorganization.com, rushcard.io, discordapp.com, imgur.com, youtube.com, cubiccreativity.wordpress.com, trinityygo.wixsite.com.

Spright decks in the last format were hindered by two things, needing to play bystials, and Toad being the best thing you could possibly do with the deck. With the toad line essentially gone in any competitive capacity, the deck can develop into something exciting and robust. 

Spright is no longer a single line of play ending on a double toad negate but is something that can shift and adapt its plays based on what they are playing against, with an easy iblee line (starting with gigantic summoning iblee then iblee into sprind for a bounce later on) allows the deck freedom to set up truly unhinged boards while their opponent is stuck waiting for their econ or eclipse. 

The deck I developed does not use the bujinki link as it requires too much investment for so little payoff. Using up all your resources for a single negate that can bring back a nimble is just not good enough. While the frogs are still powerful extenders, without ronin they really don't eccrue advantage like the deck needs without drawing another water. 

Since the deck lost its most important grind tool in elf, I thought about ways that could replace it, at least in a phantom sense. To do this I had to look at the most valuable aspects of elf and found 2. The first was the ability to recur and maintain resources and the second is the ability to get multiple omni negates per turn. These were fairly easy to solve as there are multiple in archetype options for both these. For the first I looked towards double cross. Double cross can either be a disruption to inturupt your opponent by stealing their important combo piece from either the field or the GY, or a way to recur a card from your GY. With double cross you can still special blue then add pixies to ensure that your monsters don't get walked over as easily. Another way we solve this is with mannequin cat. Mannequin cat is a fantastic addition to the extra deck that was only used before to get out end of anubis and dother janky cards, but everyone overlooked simply summoning back a blue or jet if they summon a dark, red/carrot if your oponant summons ira, or even a ghost ogre if they summon a light.

to solve the second, we simple look at carrot, red, and the 12 hand traps (13 if you play something other than the gamma package) to dusrupt our opponent. We no longer have to cram in as many bystials as we can and can use other cards to be able to hinder our opponent's plays. While I will admit that I would prefer to have 12 hand traps and a toad negate, I still believe that the follow up allowed in mannequin cat and the much overlooked bounce that sprind has are enough.

deck_description:
I found it. Something even more degenerate than before.

For your full combo, you just need any 1 discardable card in hand. The rest is extra/uneeded for your standard line.

You may notice that this deck is playing little to no extenders, and that would be because you do not need them. Any card in your hand that isn't a power staple, floodgate, or hand-trap is undesirable, as this deck has almost flawless consistency, besides some truly god atrocious hands where you draw every single orcust/phantom knight in a deck of 60 cards.

Player position is very important for your combo due to the link arrows, so keep that in mind when choosing where to sit on the table.

If you want me to talk about how the deck actually functions (which you have all the right in the world to do lol, that's why there is a description), you aim to abuse the fact that Grinder Golem as a DM is absolutely broken:

1 - It is a DARK, so you have access to verte + dpe, all the small Bystials, the entire Orcust engine (besides the knightmares), millennium eyes as an extra copy of called by the grave, the entire PK engine, Accesscode Talker  as the best link-4 finisher in the game, Time Thief Redoer  which is extra annoying in a free-for-all, and no one less than the True King of All Calamities (which comes up when using orcusts + PK's).


2 - It is a Fiend, so you actually have access to all the Knightmares, which are arguably the best cards ever printed in terms of versatility and ease of use, and also especially help this deck in making any 2 monsters w/ different names FULL ORCUST + PK COMBO :))

3 - And if all that wasn't enough, it's utility as a premium starter is made even better by the Deck Master Rules, which means that you can not only loop it by bouncing it back to your hand w/ Akashic Magician and Security Dragon, any time Grinder Golem leaves the field, after all efects resolve and priority is passed back to you, you may opt to pay LP in incremental amounts to bring it back to the DMZ, from where you can summon him from, again and again, non-once per turn.

So basically, make DPE, make redoer, set up a vfd on your oponent's turn and set 5. Simple enough, the line doesn't change much.


Thanks a lot to "That person you hate#6076" and "Person#4260" (couldn't find them on YGOProdeck) on the discord for actually going and playing the game with me through TTS, and managing to face Orcust BS repeatedly without DDoS'ing me.

deck_name: Truth of the world Sin world
deck_description: Malefic is non meta deck....who cares!? as long as you're happy playing using your favorite deck that's how yugioh supposed to be.

I never liked the deck Bakura had in the anime, so I tried remaking his deck while keeping some of the iconic cards he used.

In the original duel, Bakura played a shadow game where Yugi's friends were their favorite cards. The duel is super short and anticlimactic. Not to mention that Ryou Bakura cheated by not following the effect of Change of Heart (didn’t take control of the opponent's monster).

In a reimagined duel, I would have the rules of the shadow game stay the same but focus more on tormenting Yugi using cards like: Change of Heart, Possessed Dark Soul, Creature Swap, Monster Reborn, and Exchange. Bakura would take control of Yugi’s friends and Yugi would have to decide between destroying his friends or losing the duel. 

Bakura’s reimagined deck focuses on Spirits that come back to the hand at the end of turn. Fully utilizing the psychological torment of making Yugi attack his friends and referencing his dark past. The spirits of Kul Elna still fuel his malice that empowers Zorc.

Had to include cards that originally existed outside of Duelist kingdom but wanted to keep the decks fairly simple.

Kept a lot of the Machine cards that Bandit Keith used but had to add some cards that existed outside of Duelist Kingdom. Loved the idea of Bandit Keith summoning 3 Battle Footballer using Archfiend’s Staff of Despair and Machine Duplication. Between the Battling Footballer referencing American football and Barrel Dragon referencing America's love of guns, his future decks will really lean into that stereotype.

deck_excerpt: P.U.N.K. ABC for Master Duel ft. Ancient Fairy Dragon
deck_description: P.U.N.K. ABC for Master Duel ft. Ancient Fairy Dragon

Really disappointed in Pumpking the King of Ghosts real life effect. I have no idea why that card is supposed to be played with Castle of Dark Illusions, but it definitely wouldn’t have that effect in a reimagined duel. Loved the idea that Joey would bring out his Red-Eyes, Bonz would get over it, then Bonz reborns it and tributes it to summon Red-Eyes Zombie Dragon.

Didn’t know what to do about Flame Swordsman. It’s a fusion in real life, and a normal monster in the anime. Thought about changing the reimagined anime to have his beloved card be the Blue Flame Swordsman but decided against it and kept the Flame Swordsman a fusion. 

Decided that cards like Megamorph and Sword of Dragon’s Soul would be cards that Solomon would have given Joey to use in case he ever battle’s Kaiba. Any decent deck should have an out to Blue-Eyes. I know Megamorph was used by Kaiba but it didn’t really feel like a card he would use. That card implies that you know you will be losing at some point and Joey definitely embodies the “come-from-behind”/ “underdog”/ ”underestimated” mentality.
Kept Kaiba’s deck really close to the anime. I gave him “Riryoku” since “Negative Energy Generator” is too overpowered. Imagine if Yugi could use that on “Summoned Skull”!

Couldn’t decide if she should use Harpie Lady 1,2,3 or if she should start with 3 copies of the Normal Monster Harpie Lady. I went with Harpie Lady 1,2,3 because of how few monsters she has. Originally, she had more WIND Winged-Beast monsters but she was unbeatable in test duels. In the anime, Mai’s weakness was that she only powered up 1 monster, so I kept that the same. If you can beat Harpie Lady Sisters with all the power ups, you win.

This duel in the anime was a mess. Konami had to release “Attack the Moon!” just to have it make any sense. In a reimagined duel his monsters wouldn’t be hiding underwater, but behind Tornado Wall. Legendary Fisherman would be equipped with Ballista of Rampart Smashing (the only equip spell that looks like a harpoon).

In the anime, Mokuba steals a random deck to duel Yugi. Seeing no reason to change that, I wanted to show what the “average” deck looked like. Mokuba would draw his opening hand and just be disgusted with this random deck. 

What I actually did though was compile a bunch of cards that I hated as a kid mixed in with some Mokuba type cards. Had to give him Cyber-Stein and Gale Dogra just to give him a way to summon some fusions that I felt Mokuba would use. 

Seriously, if someone got me this “structure deck Mokuba” garbage as a gift, I’d be upset.

As the tagline said, I decided to build Krawler in a weird way. 

As you're gonna see pretty quickly, I decided to pair it with World Legacy. Now, if you take aside that they come from the same lore, there is a true reason to pair these archetypes. To play the game, the Deck mainly needs its Spell and Trap cards : World Legacy Pawns gives you a way to interact with your opponent, reactivate your Flip effects and allows you to play way faster ; World Legacy in Shadow transform every of your Krawler into the best way of removal in the game and gives a Special Summon ; and World Leagcy's Mind Meld gives you a negate and a free + 2.

But to search these cards, your only option in a "normal" Krawler Deck is survivor, a really good card that cannot do everything. Thats where your "Worls Legacy" monsters. World Armor searches a Spell/trap or another monster, can Special Summon itself and in some rare cases can bounce an Extra Deck monster of your opponent. World Chalice is your main target for Dendrite Krwaler as it allows you to search a Spell/Trap the turn after it was sent to the Graveyard ; allows you to spawnkill one of your opponent's Extra Deck monster and can eventually unbrick you. World Crown is a free extender and a negate of an Extra Deck monster's effect. Finally, World Wand specials a monster from your hand when send to the Graveyard, generally via Dendrite. All of these monster anable a great extra Deck monster : Lib the World Key Blademaster. This monster gives you one of your Spell/Traps if there is a World Legacy in your grave, which you can easily have via Dendrite. It can do that in every of your Main Phases so you're not running out of steam. Its even a great removal if you use it as Link Material or is simply removed by your opponent.

For the Krawler side, Survivor and Receptor ensure that you have access to every monster you need. Soma is probably one of the best monster ever, simply special two monsters from your Deck or Graveyard, what could go wrong. Glial reborns or special from your hand to swarm. Deus is a one-sided Skill Drain if you Flip it that you can recycle pretty much infinietly. Every Krawler except the last one floats into two others if they are removed because of an opponents card effect, which even applies if they are banished or returned to the hand. 

I hope you enjoy this deck.
for my OC Cylie Heavenly

I made this deck to test without hand traps, as to be honest, they are all bricks after turn 1. Thus, I run board breakers which I found to be more useful after turn 1. As you may have noticed, this is to stop banish-based decks but has some cards to get around other strategies ie. Swordsoul. I have been getting some good results at my locals with this build.

Marincess players will notice that the chokepoint for their decks are the normal summons. Prevent the normal summon with eclipse, banish or pop it and you lose. I run Vrains and Icejade Tremora to get around this particular choke point. I currently run 2 of each as they do come up and plan on testing other cards as well. Do keep in mind that Blue Slug, Anemone, Dive, and Coral Triangle are the ones that lock you to waters if you activate their effects, so you can get away with running non-waters before activating their effects. Also keep in mind that Argonaut, Marbled Rock, and Bubble Reef just require any water monster and not just Marincess. The other chokepoint is the field spell. Most opponents I face forget about hitting the field spell so I can get away with not protecting it, but that field spell does give you the attack power. Last reminder, Coral Triangle has a grave effect if you control no monsters but your opponent does, making rebuilding your board super easy by summoning the Anemone and Sea Angel back.

If they have monsters that you cant climb, link into Zealantis as you are locked to waters and your monsters come back and theirs do not.

Edit: After further testing, this build CAN OTK but requires either Link into the Vrains or Icejade in opening hand. The idea is to go Zealantis, banish all monsters, then summon back only waters (because at this point you are locked to waters if you link climbed). Then, with all the comboing you should have a marincess in hand to climb again into Bubble Reef or enough gas in the grave or already on field. Link climb into Bubble Reef, Battle Ocean attach 3 materials, making her 4600. Sleepy Maiden in grave to attach another material, makes her 5200. 7700 damage here with Zealantis at 2500 and if you have a water in hand, you can pitch to summon a banished marincess and attack for game or if you milled 2 marincess cards off Springirl. Once I get the OTK combo down through further practice I can go into further detail, but this is the gist of how the board will look like for OTK.

deck_excerpt: The P.U.N.Ks are now full power in Masterduel!
deck_description:
Since its inception, PUNK has gained notoriety as an engine, enabling 1 card OTKs, Halq/Auroradon combo without normal summon and etc. Competitively, PUNK was only viable as an engine smushed into goodstuff decks – it was never good “pure.”

This all changes with the release of the "Sprites of Miracle" pack in Masterduel, with two new ridiculously strong PUNK support cards printed in the set! The field spell “Extreme Session” is an extender AND pot of greed, all in one card! Dragon Drive searches any level 3 psychic tuner on summon (including Ghost Ogre) and is also an extender if your opponent chains to your PUNK effect!

Extreme Session and Dragon Drive enable a mass handtrap playstyle for PUNK, allowing it to still fight through board wipes like the all-too-common Dark Ruler No More! This support granted the previously unfit engine to top competitively – all on its own archetypal legs!


Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

This deck is a variant of my "Pure PUNK" deck guide I made last year, so If you want a complete guide with all the combos, tips and gameplant, visit my Pure PUNK article linked here.
 
Small World is amazing since it replaces a brick in your hand to add one of your starters! The following are Small World search combos:
  • Activate Small World -> Any Orochi/Effect Veiler -> D.D. Crow -> Obtain PUNK Ogre Dance (starts PUNK combo line)
  • Activate Small World -> Psy-Frame Gamma/Effect Veiler -> Nibiru -> Obtain PUNK Foxy Tune (starts PUNK combo line)
  • Activate Small World -> Ash Blossom/Ghost Ogre -> PUNK Deer Note -> Any Level 3 Punk Tuner (starts PUNK combo line)
  • Activate Small World -> Any Level 3 Punk Tuner -> Effect Veiler -> Ash Blossom/Ghost Belle (I usually do this if I have all combo pieces already)
There are more Small World combos out in this deck and that can be included in, but these are the ones I primarily use. Feel free to experiment and add more!

With the disappearance of Halqifibrax, this is Pure PUNK's standard combo:
  1. Summon Ze Amin. Activate effect to search for Foxy Tune. 
  2. Activate Foxy Tune's effect to summon from deck Sharakusai. 
  3. Activate Sharakusai's effect to fusion summon Ze Amin + Sharakusai -> Rising Carp. 
  4. Activate Rising Carp's effect to summon Wa Gon and Deer Note from deck. 
  5. Activate Wa Gon's effect to search for Extreme Session. Activate Extreme Session. 
  6. Synchro Wa Gon + Deer Note -> Dragon Drive. 
  7. CL1 Dragon Drive to search Madame Spider from deck. CL2 Deer Note to summon Sharakusai from GY. On resolution, Extreme Session draws you 1 card. 
  8. Activate Extreme Session's effect summon Madame Spider from hand
  9. Activate Madame Spider's effect to search for your PUNK trap of choice (I personally prefer Nashiwari Surprise). On resolution, Extreme Session draws you 1 card. 
This is the standard Pure PUNK combo. This combo grants you a bounce of up to 4 cards on the field with Sharakusai's quick synchro into Amazing Dragon on the opponent's turn. Amazing Dragon is also follow-up for next turn, since it generates resources by summoning any PUNK from the GY. You also have a pop any card/negate monster of with your PUNK trap. Finally, Extreme Session drew you two cards, which may be hand traps, or follow-up for next turn.

Note that if you have extenders, you can make Baronne or Psychic End Punisher.


GLHF Duelists!

deck_name: Artifact + DPE + Dark Angel with guide (Master Duel)
deck_excerpt: Transform Vision hero Increase brick in a triple floodgate turn 1
deck_description:
EN: Okay, this is an experiment, but it's an idea of how to get rid of that horrible Faris + Increase hand, turning it into DPE + Dadga + dark Angel. The deck can run with one less increase or one more A hero lives, but I think it's interesting to keep it the way it is, because a hand that theoretically would be a brick now has a high potential, but with certain costs.

 

Playing hero on turn 1 has a standard combo that, depending on the missing piece, can cause a high resource expenditure to only result in a dpe + something. The piece that we all cry when we see it in our hand is the increase, because we usually optimize it by 1 card and, therefore, the Faris -> Increase -> Vyon combo will be dead. This deck list tries to get around this problem by adding 3 cards to the main deck and 2 to the extra deck.

 

The added cards work like that: First, it is important to have one more hero card to be able to perform the combo, it can be any level 4, but preferably we want the stratos, to look for another card, and it could even be Increase itself (for so he is at 3 and we have 2 E-emergency calls). From that moment on, Summon Level 4 hero -> Special Summon Faris (Discarding Increase) -> Don't use the effect of Faris, because it will lock you into heroes -> Use your 2 monsters to make Isolde, Noble knight -> Effect from Isolde to look for Denier -> Activate Isolde's effect again (sends White Veil to the graveyard) to summon renaud -> Activate Renaud's effect (returns white veil to hand) -> Uses white veil on any of the 2 -> Summon Cross cruzader using the 2 as material -> (and now things get weird) White veil activates the effect causing 3000 damage -> Increase effect in the graveyard activates, bringing it back to the Spell/trap card area -> Activates effect of Increase in Cross Crusader -> Summons Vyon -> Malicious in the cemetery -> effect of vyon (ban Faris) for Polymerization -> Use the 2 monsters to cross-Sheep -> Polymerization -> DPE in the Cross-sheep area -> Bring back Stratos -> his effect activates -> dark Angel for hand -> stratus + cross-sheep for artifact Dagda -> Use the effect of Dpe to destroy itself and destroy Dagda-> activate the effect of Dagda and bring Artifact Scythe to the zone of spell/trap card-> summon dark angel on the opponent's field.

 

Next turn the DPE comes back so use it to destroy Scythe, now your opponent can't use spell card (unless they get rid of dark Angel), and can't summon from extra deck because of Artifact's effect.

Note: Just be careful when using A hero Lives, as the white veil combo will only leave you with 1000 health.

PT-BR: Ok, esse é um experimento, mas é uma ideia de como nos livrar daquela mão horrivel de Faris + Increase, transformando ela em DPE + Dadga + dark Angel. O deck pode rodar com um increase a menos e um A hero lives a mais, mas acho interessante manter do jeito que está, pois uma mão que teoricamente seria um brick agora tem um potencial alto, porém com certos custos.

Jogar de hero no turno 1 tem um combo padrão que, dependendo da peça que faltar, pode causar um gasto de recurso alto pra resultar somente em um dpe + alguma coisa. A peça que todos nós choramos quando vemos na nossa mão é o increase, pois normalmente otimizamos ela em 1 carta e, sendo assim, o combo de Faris -> Increase -> Vyon estará morto. Essa deck list tenta contornar esse problema adicionando 3 cartas ao deck principal e 2 no extra deck.

As cartas adicionadas funcionam da seguinte maneira: Primeiro é importante ter uma carta a mais de heroi pra poder realizar o combo, pode ser qualquer nivel 4, mas preferencialmente queremos o stratos, pra procurar outra carta, podendo ser até mesmo o próprio Increase(por isso ele está em 3 e temos 2 E- emergency call). A partir desse momento, Invoca o hero Nivel 4 -> Invocação especial Faris (descartando Increase) -> Não use o efeito do faris, porque isso te travará em heróis -> Use seus 2 monstros para fazer a Isolde, Noble knight -> Efeito de Isolde para procurar Denier -> Ativa novamente o efeito de Isolde (manda White Veil para o cimitério) para invocar renaud -> Ativa effeito de Renaud (retorna white veil para mão) -> Usa white veil em qualquer um dos 2-> Invoque Cross cruzader usando os 2 como material  -> (e agora as coisas ficam estranhas) White veil ativa o efeito causando 3000 de dano -> efeito do Increase no cimitério ativa, trazendo-o devolta pra area de Spell/trap card -> Ativa efeito do increase no Cross Crusader -> Invoca Vyon -> Malicios no cimitério-> efeito do vyon (bane Faris) para Polymerização -> Use os 2 montros para fazer cross-Sheep -> Polymerização -> DPE na área do Cross-sheep -> Traga de volta Stratos -> efeito dele ativa -> dark Angel para mão -> stratus + cross-sheep para artifact Dagda -> Use o efeito do Dpe para se destruir e destruir Dagda-> ative o efeito de Dagda e traga Artifact Scythe para zone de spell/trap card-> invoque dark angel no campo adversário.

No próximo turno o DPE volta então use ele para destruir o Scythe, agora seu oponente não pode usar spell card (a não ser que se livre do dark Angel), e não pode invocar do extra deck por causa do efeito do Artifact.

Nota: Tome somente cuidado ao usar A hero Lives, pois o combo com white veil te deixará somente com 1000 de vida.

This deck was created by ChatGPT out of boredom. This is all the information it gives for this deck:

This deck focuses on the D/D archetype's ability to summon a variety of powerful boss monsters, with a focus on using Dark Contracts to search for or summon the necessary pieces. The Extra Deck includes a mix of Fusion, Synchro, Xyz, and Link monsters to provide versatility in different situations. Of course, this is just one possible way to construct a D/D deck, and the exact composition may depend on individual player preference and playstyle.

This side deck includes a mix of cards to help the deck adapt to various matchups and situations. The three monsters in the side deck are all versatile options that can help in different scenarios. Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion can disrupt your opponent's graveyard plays, Artifact Lancea can help shut down decks that rely on banishing, and Dinowrestler Pankratops can help with removal and be a decent body on the field.

The spells in the side deck are focused on helping to clear problematic cards from your opponent's side of the field. Twin Twisters and Cosmic Cyclone can help with backrow removal, while Dark Ruler No More can help bypass opposing monster effects for a turn. Instant Fusion can help with Extra Deck plays or can be used for Link Summoning.

The traps in the side deck provide a mix of defensive and offensive options. Evenly Matched can help you come back from a losing position by clearing your opponent's field, Red Reboot can help get around opposing traps, and Solemn Judgment can provide a powerful counter to any plays that your opponent makes.The main card in a D/D deck is typically considered to be D/D Savant Kepler. Kepler is a key piece in the deck's engine, as it allows you to search out your Dark Contract spells, which are crucial for summoning your D/D boss monsters and generating advantage. Kepler is also a level 1 Tuner monster, which can be useful for Synchro Summoning or Link Summoning.

That being said, the D/D archetype as a whole is designed to work cohesively as a team, with many of the cards supporting each other to create powerful combos and field presence. The deck can generate a lot of advantage and summon a variety of different boss monsters, so it's difficult to pinpoint a single "main card" in the traditional sense. Rather, the strength of a D/D deck comes from its ability to adapt to different situations and playstyles.

deck_excerpt: Kashtira can do wonders, even with birbs
deck_description:
Kashtira: an archetype hellbent on the number "7" has made a dayview in the competitive scene within days of its release. Already having surprising tops and even running the money at the most Recent YCS as of recording the gameplay (in Lyon, France). There is a lot of potential for many hybrid Kashtira builds, so I decided to make a (subtle, yet surprisingly not so terrible attempt) at using the smol birb engine (not Floowandereeze) to add a stack on this other LV7 birb that can negate anything during either players turn by returning itself to the hand (*cough* Mist Valley Apex Avian *cough*). And out the ten matches I played, I was able to get the big omni birb at least 7 times; but doesn't mean "Simorgh, Bird of perfection" went to waste however. As it was a perfect XYZ material piece for "Time Thief - Redoer" alongside "Kashtira Riseheart" (who is also LV4 btw).

 

   Not to mention that Simorgh was helped that the odds of getting Simorgh increased tenfold with the unintentional Zeus fodder "Raidraptor - Arsenal Falcon": who simply can detach one material to SS any LV4 Winged-Beast (which means it can SS Simorgh, bird of Perfection); or can be triggered to SS from the hand on Arsenal Falcon's XYZ summon. All of this to search out "Elborz, the Sacred Lands of Simorgh": which helps making summoning Apex Avian easier in case "Kashtira Birth" was not present on the field, all for then to summon an additional Winged-Beast Monster.

This deck is for the legend anthology fest

deck_excerpt: "The light thinks it travels the fastest, but it always comes to see the darkness got there first."
deck_description:
This is a deck that I built right at home, and is also the most powerful deck I have ever built in real life! It has about 3-4 different ways it can kill you, and I'll go down the list here:

 

    1. [OPTIONAL] Crush them with "Obelisk the Tormentor".
        This is a relativly easy task if you're experienced enough with the deck. For those of you who live under a bridge (or new players who were just introdcued to the franchise), summoning Obelisk requires three sacrifices. However, cards such as "Soul Crossing" make this much easier, as it allows you to sacrifice three or less of your opponent's monsters instead, however, if your opponent only has let's say two monsters, then you'll need tyo sacrifice your own monsters to summon him. Using his abilities will not be difficult, as the field spell "Lair of Darkness" allows you to sacrfice one of your opponent's monsters along with one of yours to destroy all monsters he/she controls.

    2. Burning them with "Bad Reaction to Simochi".
        This card is one of my favourites, as it negates any Lifepoints that your opponent would gain, and drains that many Lifepoints instead. It's great for giving your opponent the middle finger with. Now, the cool part about this, is that some cards would initially let you do certain things at the price of healing your opponent, however, with "Bad Reaction to Simochi", you essentially get to do these things for free, as well as damage your opponent. While there aren't really cards that do this in this deck, however, you'll notice that there are three "Gift Card"s in this deck, a card that just gives your opponent three-thousand Lifepoints. Or at least it would if it weren't for Simochi turning it into damage.

    3. Butcher them with "Litmus Doom Swordsman".
        "Litmus Doom Swordsman" is the most powerful Ritual Monster I own, and honestly the most powerful Ritual Monster I've ever seen (then again I haven't seen enough other Ritual monsters to really know if there's others more powerful than him). Litmus is a monster that functions around Traps, something this deck has plenty of. He comes to the battlefield completely immune to trap effects and cannot be destroyed by battle, and, while there is a trap on the field, he has three-thousand attack points. Now, there is another card in this deck called "Djinn Demolisher of Rituals". If you can get this card in your graveyard, you can banish him from there in addition to your Ritual sacrifice to make Litmus immune to your opponent's card effects, on top of all of his other immunities. So you baiscally have an invincible monster on your side of the field. Definently not broken, right?

    4. Miscellanious
        I have grouped all of the other ways this deck can kill into one group, since it's basically just "oh yeah just kill him with 'Doomcaliber Knight'", or "just burn them to death with 'Lava Golem' or 'Ectoplasmer' comboed with 'Malice Doll of Demise'". This catagory is just every other one-or-two-card combo in this deck that can kill.

I hope you guys like my deck! :)

Also both normal summon without tribute and banish FACE DOWN effect are incredible. 

Dracosacc + cherubini is a must now that all 3 main deck names are limited. Alternatively beatrice with diviner and mikanko, but that means your main combo requires a normal summon, a discard, play bricks in main deck, not flexible at all. 

Belle is debatable and can be replaced but she does protect your tearlaments from banish effects. Edit: Replaced with contact "c", nibiru isn't bad but half of the deck is kashtira, and both won't stop hard make ariseheart anyway. Edit#2: Replaced contact "C" with lancea, lancea almost never feels bad in hand and almost always soften opponent turn enough for you to break board on your turn. Imperm is good but because of chimera the monster count must always stay at a certain level. Another idea is to main 1 pank and 2 lancea.

No foolish burial of burial goods because i personally don't find them to do enough. Edit: I still don't find them doing enough in important match up. Edit#2: yeah those 2 are definitely out.

Borreload and garura are also replacable depends on how meta will shape. Edit, moved borrel and 1 copy of zeus out in favor for linguriboh and donner. Edit#2: Move dharc out for link 3 black luster. You can absolutely play without him but he is like the "simplify match up against trap decks" button this format.

deck_description:
The deck uses powerful, cheap trap cards to control the game and eventually win the game through a slow grind. The main way the deck works is, by using Bearblocker to protect all of our set traps and Dark Eye Nightmare to refuel the hand during the later game. When the deck runs into a hard-to-remove monster Castel, the Skyblaster Musketeer can spin it back to the deck. Sometimes if the deck is working you may find yourself without a way to close out the game, Wave-Motion Cannon hopes to solve that problem. 

Overall, the deck works well for being so and can sometimes hold its own against higher-costing decks. One last comment I have to add is, this deck works well for newer players to the game since it's so cheap and has such a simple game plan.

deck_excerpt: I swear this one has been thought through. Honest.
deck_description:
Blue-Eyes White Dragon is the cornerstone of this deck, everything revolves around it. Alternative gets itself out for free if you have one in your hand, and Jet does the same with just one kill. White Stone is a free summon of a BEWD, Jet, Dragon Spirit, or Solid. The Eyes of Blue Spellcasters can either go into your Synchros or just help to cycle more beatsticks. As for your Spells... Cards of Consonance, Trade-In, and Melody can cycle out your bricks for immediate advantage, especially since a lot of cards here which are bricks in the hand are much better in the Graveyard, where they're legitimate targets for Return of the Dragon Lords, Silvers Cry, or even Ultimate Fusion. Bingo is just a card-neutral trade-in for whatever Blue-Eyes card you need right at that moment. Imperm and Effect Veiler are just your good hand traps if you're struggling with Monster Effects.

Your Extra Deck is pretty self-explanatory. Fusion Monsters all work with Ultimate Fusion, and can be brought out pretty easily if you can cycle enough Blue-Eyes into hand, deck, or GY (with the bonus of resetting Alternative if you're forced to dump it, since it can't be resurrected without originally being brought out legitimately). Synchros help you get another strong monster on the board, with the available Tuners - particularly White Stone - giving you opportunities to resurrect used materials. All XYZs are Rank 8, and you can just bring out whichever one you need depending on what interests you the most at a given moment - Harbinger for anti-Spell, Heliopolis for board wipe potential, and Galaxy-Eyes for a strong beatstick with once-per-turn targeted removal. As for Links, Borrelsword is just your incredible beatdown, and Hieratic Seal is a Speed 2 Bounce that can also bring out another Dragon when no longer needed.

Your Side Deck is your basic counterpicks. Ash Blossom is here for when you're struggling with an opponent who heavily deck summons, Twin Twisters have backrow removal, and the Solemns are for if you really need Summon negation. There's also an extra copy each of Consonance, Trade-In, and Silver's Cry, if you feel like your opponent is lacking the ability to block your draw engine or restrict your Graveyard Special Summons, and you want to push that advantage further. Dictator of D is also here for that same reason, in addition to the attack control it offers.

This is honestly made to be a fairly straightforward pure Blue-Eyes deck - obviously, I could've added a different engine to it, but I wanted to use as few other archetypes as possible in the main deck. I've tried to design it to be as beginner-friendly as possible, to the point where a lot of the deck plays itself if you know the abilities of the cards involved. Might not be perfect, probably has a few flaws that I'm not immediately noticing, but I'm liking how it looks. Hopefully works as a decent Rogue deck.
